"Junghans N., Cullmann J., Huss M.","Evaluating the effect of snow and ice melt in an Alpine headwater catchment and further downstream in the River Rhine [Evaluation de l'effet de la fonte de neige et de glace dans un bassin versant alpin amont et plus à l'aval sur le Rhin]",2011,"Hydrological Sciences Journal","56","6",,"981","993",,,10.1080/02626667.2011.595372,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052163852&partnerID=40&md5=2c7b887bc37038e850c9f8422c648d62","An den drei Teichen 13, D-09395 Hormersdorf, Germany; IHP/HWRP-Sekretariat, Bundesanstalt für Gewässerkunde, Postfach 200253, D-56002 Koblenz, Germany; Department of Geosciences, University of Fribourg, Chemin du Musée 4, CH-1700 Fribourg, Switzerland","Junghans, N., An den drei Teichen 13, D-09395 Hormersdorf, Germany; Cullmann, J., IHP/HWRP-Sekretariat, Bundesanstalt für Gewässerkunde, Postfach 200253, D-56002 Koblenz, Germany; Huss, M., Department of Geosciences, University of Fribourg, Chemin du Musée 4, CH-1700 Fribourg, Switzerland","The runoff regime of glacierized headwater catchments in the Alps is essentially characterized by snow and ice melt. High Alpine drainage basins influence distant downstream catchments of the Rhine River basin. In particular, during the summer months, low-flow conditions are probable with strongly reduced snow and ice melt under climate change conditions. This study attempts to quantify present and future contributions from snow and ice melt to summer runoff at different spatial scales. For the small Silvretta catchment (103 km 2) in the Swiss Alps, with a glacierization of 7%, the HBV model and the glacio-hydrological model GERM are applied for calculating future runoff based on different regional climate scenarios. We evaluate the importance of snow and ice melt in the runoff regime. Comparison of the models indicates that the HBV model strongly overestimates the future contribution of glacier melt to runoff, as glaciers are considered as static components. Furthermore, we provide estimates of the current meltwater contribution of glaciers for several catchments downstream on the River Rhine during the month of August. Snow and ice melt processes have a significant direct impact on summer runoff, not only for high mountain catchments, but also for large transboundary basins. A future shift in the hydrological regime and the disappearance of glaciers might favour low-flow conditions during summer along the Rhine. © 2011 IAHS Press.","Climate scenarios; Glacier retreat; Global warming; Ice melt; Model comparison; River Rhine; Snow melt","Climate scenarios; Glacier retreat; Model comparison; River Rhine; Snow melt; Catchments; Climate models; Glaciers; Global warming; Rivers; Runoff; Snow; Ice; alpine environment; catchment; climate change; climate effect; climate modeling; drainage basin; glacier retreat; headwater; ice; low flow; meltwater; mountain stream; quantitative analysis; runoff; snowmelt; spatial variation; streamflow; summer; Alps; Central Alps; Rhine Basin; Hepatitis B virus",,,,,,"Braun, L., Weber, M., Schulz, M., Consequences of climate change for runoff from Alpine regions (2000) Annals of Glaciology, 31 (1), pp. 19-25; (2009) Hydrologisches Jahrbuch der Schweiz 2008, , BAFU (Bundesamt für Umwelt), Umwelt-Wissen Nr. 0921. Bern, Switzerland: Bundesamt für Umwelt; Deutsches Gewässerkundliches Jahrbuch, Rheingebiet, , BfG (Bundesanstalt für Gewässerkunde), Teil I und Teil III. Koblenz, Germany: Bundesanstalt für Gewässerkunde; Christensen, J.H., Christensen, O.B., A summary of the PRUDENCE model projections of changes in European climate by the end of this century (2007) Climatic Change, 81 (1), pp. 7-30; Farinotti, D., Huss, M., Bauder, A., Funk, M., An estimate of the glacier ice volume in the the Swiss Alps (2009) Global and Planetary Change, 68 (3), pp. 225-231. , doi:10.1016/ j.gloplacha.2009.05.004; Frei, C., Die Klimazukunft der Schweiz (2007) Klimaänderung und die Schweiz 2050-Erwartete Auswirkunge